			6.5.2016 at 16:13				</a>
						</div>

		<p>The name sdb2 means it is partition 2 of hard disk 2. Look on the mother board, there are often some numbers indicating order of disks. Slot 1 is sda, slot 2 is sdb etc. If the mother board does not have any markings, look at the BIOS messages during startup.</p>
<p>If there is no hard disk order list in the BIOS, as a last resort you might want to remove the cable of one hard drive at a time and check what the Linux startup complains about. It will tell you when sda or sdb is no longer visible.</p>

		<div class="reply"><a rel='nofollow' class='comment-reply-link' href='#comment-38822' data-commentid="38822" data-postid="3317" data-belowelement="div-comment-38822" data-respondelement="respond" data-replyto="Reply to Otto Kekäläinen" aria-label='Reply to Otto Kekäläinen'>Reply</a></div>
